

<html>
<head>
<title>Statistical Inference II Classnote</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=right><font size=-2>[Stat Inf II
classnotes, ISI, Kolkata]
</td></tr></table>
<h1>Some results about stopping time</h1>




<h3>Wald's first equation</h3>

<!-- problem idea: Ask to prove for general fn Z = f(X).-->

<table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
<b>Theorem:</b>
(Wald's first equation)
Suppose that X<sub>1</sub>,X<sub>2</sub>, ... are iid and
E|X<sub>i</sub>| is finite. Let T be any
stopping time wrt the X's such that E(T) is finite. Define for n=1,2,...

<blockquote>
S<sub>n</sub> = X<sub>1</sub>+...+X<sub>n</sub>.
</blockquote>

Then 

<blockquote>
E(S<sub>T</sub>) = E(T) E(X<sub>1</sub>).
</blockquote>


</td></tr></table>

<p>

<table><tr><td width=1 bgcolor="#cccccc"></td>
<td>
<b><i>Proof:</i></b> 
We shall break the proof into a number of exercises.
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT3.1:</font></b> 
   
   First show that
   
   <blockquote>
   E(S<sub>T</sub>) = E 
                        <img src=
                        "resources/statinf2/sum.gif"
                        align=middle>
                        
                         X<sub>n</sub> 
   I<sub>T &gt; n-1</sub>.
   </blockquote>
   
   Here the summation is an infinite series over n=1,2,...upto infinity.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
There is a theorem (called Fubini's theorem, as you'll learn in MI
measure theory course) which allows us to interchange expectation and
infinite summation whenever each summand is integrable (we call a random
variable U integrable if E|U| is finite.) 

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT3.2:</font></b> 
   
   Argue that each summand in the infinite series above is indeed
   integrable. So you can bring the expectation inside the summation. Hence
   prove Wald's first equation.<br>
   <br>
       <i>[Hint:
       
       You may like to use the following exercise.]
       </i>
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT3.3:</font></b> 
   
   Show 
    that if a random variable U takes only
   nonnegative integer values, then 
   
   <blockquote>
   E(U) = P(U &gt; 0)+P(U &gt; 1)+P(U &gt; 2)+...
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<img src="resources/statinf2/square.gif">
</td></tr></table>
</blockquote>


<h4>An amusing consequence</h4>

Suppose there is a gambling scheme with expected value 0. If you play it
n many times, then your expected payoff remains zero, whatever n may
be. You may think that this fact would dissuade a gambler from wasting
money in the casino. However, it doesn't. Gamblers like to think
themselves smart, and they would say, "I never play for a fixed number of
times. The moment I win a goodly amount, say Rs 500 I quit playing, and
go home with that amount. I just don't take any further risk. That keeps
me from getting ruined, you see! Again, if my loss exceeds Rs 100.00, I
quit. This keeps my loss under control." Real gamblers may come up with
even more complicated clever schemes as to the right time to stop playing
so that you keep your profit intact, without risking too much loss. It may
be mind-boggling to counter all their arguments, but Wald's first equality
shows in one single stroke that howsoever cleverly the gambler chooses his
stopping time, his expected payoff always remains zero. 


<h4>What if E(T) is infinite?</h4>

For Wald's first equation we need E(T) to be finite. Here is what may
happen if this condition is not met.
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#995555"></td>
   <td>
   <b>Example:</b> 
   
   Let X<sub>i</sub>'s be iid with the following distribution
   
   <blockquote>
   
   
   <table border=0>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
   X<sub>i</sub> = 
   </td>
   <td>
   1
   </td>
   <td align=left>
    with probability 0.5
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
                   
   </td>
   <td>
   -1
   </td>
   <td align=left>
    with probability 0.5
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   </table>
   
   
   </blockquote>
   
   Thus we have a simple symmetric random walk. Consider the stopping time T
   which is the first time an S<sub>i</sub> is 1. Thus,
   
   <blockquote>
   {T = n} is same as {S<sub>i</sub>
                                    <img src=
                                    "resources/statinf2/neq.png"
                                    align=top>
                                    
                                     1 for i &lt; n, and
   S<sub>n</sub> = 1}.
   </blockquote>
   
   The following exercises will explore if Wald's first equation holds here.
   
   
   <p>
      <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
      <td>
      <b><font color="#cc0000">
      Exercise SPRT3.4:</font></b> 
      
      Show that 
      
      <blockquote>
      P(T is finite) = 1
      </blockquote>
      
      
      </td></tr></table>
      </blockquote>
      
   
   <p>
      <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
      <td>
      <b><font color="#cc0000">
      Exercise SPRT3.5:</font></b> 
      
      Show that
      
      <blockquote>
      E(T) = 
             <img src=
             "resources/statinf2/inf.png"
             align=top>
             
             .
      </blockquote>
      
      
      </td></tr></table>
      </blockquote>
      
   <p>
   Obviously, E(S<sub>T</sub>) = 1 (why?). So Wald's first equation takes the
   meaningless form
   
   <blockquote>
   1 = 
       <img src=
       "resources/statinf2/inf.png"
       align=top>
       
        times 0.
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   


<h3>Wald's second equation</h3>

This is similar to the first equation except that it deals with the second
moment. 
<p>

<table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
<b>Theorem:</b>
(Wald's second equality)
If T is a stopping time wrt iid 

<blockquote>
X<sub>1</sub>,X<sub>2</sub>,...
</blockquote>

such that

<blockquote>

<ul>
<li>E(T) is finite
<li>E(X<sub>i</sub>) = 0
<li>Var(X<sub>i</sub>) is finite
</ul>

</blockquote>

then

<blockquote>
Var(S<sub>T</sub>) = E(T) Var(X<sub>i</sub>)
</blockquote>


</td></tr></table>

<p>

<table><tr><td width=1 bgcolor="#cccccc"></td>
<td>
<b><i>Proof:</i></b> 

We shall not prove it in this course.
<img src="resources/statinf2/square.gif">
</td></tr></table>
</blockquote>



<h3>Wald's fundamental identity</h3>

Consider 

<blockquote>
X<sub>1</sub>,X<sub>2</sub>,... iid with some density f.
</blockquote>

Let T be some stopping time with P(T is finite) = 1.
<p>
Consider the m.g.f. defined as

<blockquote>
&phi;(t) = E(exp(t X)),
</blockquote>

where X has distribution F. Fix some t such that &phi;(t) is finite. 
Consider the density g defined as

<blockquote>
g(x) = (exp(t x)/ &phi;(t)) * f(x).
</blockquote>

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT3.6:</font></b> 
   
   Show that g is indeed a density function.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
Let 

<blockquote>
S<sub>n</sub> = X<sub>1</sub>+...+X<sub>n</sub>.
</blockquote>

<p>

<table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
<b>Theorem:</b>
(Wald's fundamental identity)
In the above set up we have

<blockquote>

E(exp(t S<sub>T</sub>)/ &phi;(t)<sup>T</sup>) = 
P<sub>g</sub>(T is finite)
</blockquote>


</td></tr></table>

<p>

<table><tr><td width=1 bgcolor="#cccccc"></td>
<td>
<b><i>Proof:</i></b> 

Let's start with the lhs. It is of the form E(h(T)) for some function h. 
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT3.7:</font></b> 
   
   Show that if h(T) is any integrable function of T, then 
   
   <blockquote>
   E(h(T)) = 
             <img src=
             "resources/statinf2/sum.gif"
             align=middle>
             
             P(T=n) E(h(T)|T=n).
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT3.8:</font></b> 
   
   Show that the conditional density of
   (X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>n</sub>)
   given T=n is
   
   <blockquote>
   f(x<sub>1</sub>)...f(x<sub>n</sub>)/P(T=n),
   </blockquote>
   
   over the set of (x<sub>1</sub>,...,x<sub>n</sub>) such that T=n. The
   density is zero outside this set. Why can we not write this set as
   
   <blockquote>
   {(x<sub>1</sub>,...,x<sub>n</sub>) :
   T(x<sub>1</sub>,...,x<sub>n</sub>)=n}?
   </blockquote>
    
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT3.9:</font></b> 
   
   Use the definition of g  and the above exercises to complete the proof.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<img src="resources/statinf2/square.gif">
</td></tr></table>
</blockquote>



